VALUES
(43, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 'In the beginning', 'Creation and the Word', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''in the beginning,'' linking the act of creation in Genesis with the existence of the Word in John. This connection highlights the foundational role of the Word in the creation narrative.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 1, 20, 8, 22, 31, 'In the beginning', 'Connection of Creation and Wisdom', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of existence ''in the beginning'' and the role of a divine figure present at creation. John 1:1 introduces the Word as being with God and as God, while Proverbs 8:22-31 describes Wisdom being present with God before the creation of the earth.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 1, 43, 1, 2, 2, 'in the beginning', 'Connection of the Word''s Existence', 'This connection highlights the continuity of the Word''s existence with God. Both passages emphasize that the Word was present ''in the beginning'' and was with God.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 1, 43, 1, 14, 14, 'the Word was God', 'Connection of the Word''s Nature', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of the Word. In John 1:1, the Word is described as God, while John 1:14 reveals the Word becoming flesh, indicating a profound connection between divinity and humanity.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 1, 51, 1, 17, 17, 'the Word was God', 'Connection of Christ''s Preeminence', 'Both passages emphasize the preexistence and divine nature of Christ. John 1:1 states that ''the Word was God,'' while Colossians 1:17 affirms that ''he is before all things.''', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 1, 62, 1, 1, 2, 'the Word', 'Connection of the Word', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''the Word'' as central to their messages. John 1:1 introduces ''the Word'' as being with God and as God, while 1 John 1:1 refers to ''the Word of life'' that was manifested and witnessed by the apostles.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 1, 66, 1, 8, 8, 'In the beginning', 'Connection of Beginning and Word', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''the beginning.'' John 1:1 introduces the Word as existing from the beginning, while Revelation 1:8 identifies the Lord as the beginning and the ending.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 3, 51, 1, 16, 17, 'All things were made by him', 'Creation by Him Connection', 'Both passages emphasize that all things were made by him, highlighting the role of the same divine figure in creation. This connection underscores the comprehensive nature of his creative authority over all realms.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 3, 46, 8, 6, 6, 'all things were made by him', 'Creation through Christ', 'Both passages emphasize that all things were made through Christ. John 1:3 states that ''without him was not any thing made,'' while 1 Corinthians 8:6 affirms that all things are by him.', 'theme', 0.7409999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 3, 66, 4, 11, 11, 'all things were made by him', 'Creation and Divine Worthiness', 'Both passages emphasize that all things were created by God, highlighting His role as the Creator. John 1:3 states that ''all things were made by him,'' while Revelation 4:11 affirms that God is worthy because ''thou hast created all things.''', 'theme', 0.6639999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 3, 19, 33, 6, 6, 'all things were made by him', 'Creation by the Word', 'Both passages emphasize the act of creation through a divine agent. John 1:3 states that ''all things were made by him,'' while Psalms 33:6 attributes the creation of the heavens to ''the word of the Lord.''', 'theme', 0.608, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 3, 1, 1, 26, 26, 'All things were made by him', 'Creation and Divine Image', 'This connection highlights the act of creation in both passages. John 1:3 states that all things were made by him, while Genesis 1:26 describes God creating man in His image, emphasizing the divine involvement in creation.', 'theme', 0.587, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 3, 43, 1, 10, 10, NULL, 'Creation and Recognition of Christ', 'Both passages emphasize that ''the world was made by him,'' highlighting the connection between Christ as the creator and the world''s failure to recognize him. This connection underscores the theme of creation and the world''s ignorance of its maker.', 'theme', 0.566, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 3, 58, 1, 2, 3, NULL, 'Creation and Divine Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Son in creation, stating that all things were made by him. This connection highlights the continuity of the theme of divine authority in the act of creation.', 'theme', 0.566, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 4, 43, 8, 12, 12, NULL, 'Connection of Light and Life', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of light as essential to life. In John 1:4, life is described as the light of men, while in John 8:12, Jesus identifies himself as the light of the world, linking light directly to life.', 'theme', 0.7899999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 4, 43, 12, 46, 46, 'the light of men', 'Connection of Light and Life', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of light as a vital element for humanity. John 1:4 states that life is the light of men, while John 12:46 presents Jesus as the light that prevents people from remaining in darkness.', 'theme', 0.734, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 4, 62, 1, 5, 7, 'the light of men', 'Light and Fellowship Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of light as a representation of divine truth and life. John 1:4 states that life is the light of men, while 1 John 1:5 declares that God is light, indicating a thematic link between divine presence and moral clarity.', 'theme', 0.622, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 4, 42, 1, 78, 79, 'light of men', 'Light in Darkness Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of light overcoming darkness. John 1:4 speaks of life as the light of men, while Luke 1:78-79 describes light given to those in darkness and the shadow of death.', 'theme', 0.538, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 4, 23, 42, 6, 7, NULL, 'Light and Life Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of light as a guiding force. John 1:4 speaks of life as the light of men, while Isaiah 42:6 refers to God giving a light to the Gentiles, suggesting a shared theme of illumination and guidance.', 'theme', 0.503, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 4, 62, 5, 11, 11, 'life', 'Connection of Life in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of life found in Christ. John 1:4 states that ''in him was life,'' while 1 John 5:11 affirms that ''this life is in his Son.''', 'theme', 0.475, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 4, 49, 5, 14, 14, 'light of men', 'Connection of Light and Life', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of light as a transformative force. John speaks of life as the light of men, while Ephesians calls for awakening to receive light from Christ.', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 5, 43, 3, 19, 20, 'the light shineth in darkness', 'Connection of Light and Darkness', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between light and darkness. John 1:5 states that ''the light shineth in darkness,'' while John 3:19-20 discusses how men ''loved darkness rather than light.''', 'theme', 0.7409999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 5, 43, 12, 36, 40, 'light shineth in darkness', 'Light and Darkness Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of light in relation to belief and understanding. The ''light'' in John 1:5 represents truth that is not comprehended by those in darkness, which is echoed in John 12:36-40, where the failure to believe leads to spiritual blindness.', 'theme', 0.629, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 5, 46, 2, 14, 14, 'darkness comprehended it not', 'Light and Spiritual Discernment', 'This connection highlights the theme of understanding spiritual truths. Both passages emphasize the inability of those in darkness or the natural man to comprehend spiritual realities.', 'theme', 0.594, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 5, 18, 24, 13, 17, 'the light shineth in darkness', 'Light and Darkness Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between light and darkness, illustrating how darkness fails to comprehend or accept the light. Job describes those who rebel against the light, paralleling the idea in John that darkness does not understand the light that shines in it.', 'theme', 0.538, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 5, 45, 1, 28, 28, 'light shineth in darkness', 'Light and Darkness Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the struggle between light and darkness, with John highlighting the inability of darkness to comprehend light, while Romans illustrates the rejection of God leading to a darkened mind. This connection highlights the consequences of turning away from divine truth.', 'theme', 0.46799999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 5, 20, 1, 22, 22, 'light shineth in darkness', 'Light and Knowledge Contrast', 'This connection highlights the contrast between light and darkness in John 1:5 and the rejection of knowledge in Proverbs 1:22. Both passages emphasize the idea that those who dwell in darkness or simplicity fail to grasp the truth and wisdom offered to them.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 5, 20, 1, 29, 30, 'darkness comprehended it not', 'Light and Knowledge Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejecting light and knowledge. In John 1:5, the darkness does not comprehend the light, paralleling Proverbs 1:29-30, where individuals despise knowledge and counsel.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 6, 39, 3, 1, 1, 'a man sent from God', 'Connection of Messengers', 'This connection highlights the role of John as a messenger sent from God, paralleling Malachi''s prophecy of a messenger who will prepare the way. Both passages emphasize the significance of these figures in relation to God''s coming.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 6, 43, 3, 28, 28, 'sent from God', 'Connection of John the Baptist''s Role', 'Both passages emphasize that John was sent from God. In John 1:6, he is introduced as a man sent from God, while John 3:28 reiterates his role of being sent before Christ.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 6, 23, 40, 3, 5, 'sent from God', 'Connection of John and Isaiah', 'This connection highlights the role of John as a forerunner, as he is ''a man sent from God'' to prepare the way for the Lord, echoing Isaiah''s call to ''Prepare ye the way of the Lord.'' Both passages emphasize the importance of preparing for God''s revelation.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 6, 42, 1, 76, 76, 'sent from God', 'Connection of John the Baptist''s Role', 'This connection highlights the role of John as a messenger. Both passages emphasize that John is sent by God to prepare the way for the Lord.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 6, 43, 1, 33, 33, 'a man sent from God', 'Connection of John the Baptist', 'This connection highlights the role of John as a messenger sent from God, emphasizing his purpose in identifying Jesus. Both passages focus on John''s mission and the divine guidance he receives regarding Jesus'' identity.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 6, 44, 13, 24, 24, 'a man sent from God', 'Connection of John the Baptist', 'This connection highlights the role of John as a messenger sent from God. Both passages emphasize John''s mission to prepare the way for Jesus through preaching and baptism.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 6, 40, 11, 10, 10, 'a man sent from God', 'Connection of John the Baptist', 'This connection highlights the role of John as a messenger sent from God. Both passages emphasize his purpose in preparing the way for Jesus.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 7, 44, 19, 4, 4, 'that all men through him might believe', 'Witness and Belief Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of belief in Christ. John 1:7 speaks of bearing witness to the Light, while Acts 19:4 refers to believing on him which should come after John, namely Christ Jesus.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 7, 43, 1, 12, 12, 'that all men through him might believe', 'Connection of Belief and Power', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of belief leading to a transformative relationship with God. The first verse highlights the purpose of witnessing to the Light for belief, while the second verse connects belief to the power of becoming sons of God.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 7, 43, 1, 32, 34, 'bear witness of the Light', 'Witness of the Light', 'Both passages emphasize the role of John as a witness to Jesus. In John 1:7, John is sent to bear witness of the Light, while in John 1:32-34, he testifies that Jesus is the Son of God, confirming his role as a witness.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 7, 56, 2, 11, 11, 'that all men through him might believe', 'Connection of Salvation and Belief', 'Both passages emphasize the universal offer of salvation. John 1:7 speaks of belief through the Light, while Titus 2:11 states that salvation has appeared to all men.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 7, 61, 3, 9, 9, 'that all men through him might believe', 'Connection of Belief and Repentance', 'Both passages emphasize the desire for all to believe and come to repentance. John 1:7 highlights the purpose of witness for belief, while 2 Peter 3:9 expresses God''s wish for all to repent.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 7, 49, 3, 9, 9, 'all men', 'Witness and Fellowship Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of revealing truth to all men. Both passages emphasize the role of Jesus Christ in bringing understanding and belief to humanity.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 7, 54, 2, 4, 4, 'all men through him might believe', 'Connection of Salvation and Belief', 'Both passages emphasize the desire for all men to believe and be saved. John 1:7 speaks of bearing witness to the Light, while 1 Timothy 2:4 expresses God''s will for all men to be saved.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 8, 43, 1, 20, 20, 'bear witness of that Light', 'Witness and Confession Connection', 'This connection highlights the role of John the Baptist as a witness to the Light, which is further emphasized in his confession of not being the Christ. Both passages focus on John''s identity and mission in relation to the true Light.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 8, 43, 3, 28, 28, 'bear witness', 'Witness to the Light', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the speaker as a witness. In John 1:8, the speaker is sent to bear witness of the Light, while in John 3:28, he clarifies that he is sent before Christ, reinforcing his role as a forerunner.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 8, 44, 19, 4, 4, 'bear witness of that Light', 'Witness of John the Baptist', 'This connection highlights John''s role as a witness to the coming of Christ. Both passages emphasize the importance of believing in the Light, which is Christ, as John pointed to Him.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 9, 43, 12, 46, 46, 'lighteth every man that cometh into the world', 'Connection of Light in John', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of light as a guiding force for humanity. John 1:9 introduces the true Light that enlightens every man, while John 12:46 presents Jesus as that light, inviting belief to escape darkness.', 'theme', 0.573, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 9, 43, 1, 4, 4, 'lighteth every man that cometh into the world', 'Connection of Light and Life', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of light as essential to humanity. John 1:4 states that ''the life was the light of men,'' while John 1:9 identifies this light as the true Light that enlightens every person.', 'theme', 0.475, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 9, 62, 2, 8, 8, 'the true Light', 'Connection of True Light', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''true Light'' that dispels darkness. John 1:9 introduces the true Light that enlightens every person, while 1 John 2:8 declares that this Light now shines, indicating a fulfillment of that promise.', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 9, 23, 49, 6, 6, 'lighteth every man that cometh into the world', 'Light as a Central Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of light in both passages. John 1:9 refers to Jesus as the true Light, while Isaiah 49:6 mentions being a light to the Gentiles, emphasizing the role of light in salvation.', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 9, 52, 5, 4, 7, 'lighteth every man that cometh into the world', 'Light and Darkness Contrast', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between light and darkness. John 1:9 speaks of the true Light that enlightens every man, while 1 Thessalonians 5:4-7 identifies believers as children of light, urging them to remain vigilant against darkness.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 9, 62, 5, 20, 20, 'true Light', 'Connection of True Light and True God', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''true'' in relation to divine revelation. John 1:9 refers to Jesus as the ''true Light,'' while 1 John 5:20 identifies Him as ''the true God.'' This connection highlights the understanding of Jesus'' divine nature.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 9, 23, 8, 20, 20, 'lighteth every man', 'Light and Guidance Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of light as a guiding force. John 1:9 speaks of the true Light that enlightens every man, while Isaiah 8:20 indicates that those without light do not speak according to God''s word.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 10, 43, 17, 25, 25, 'the world knew him not', 'Knowledge of God and the World', 'This connection highlights the theme of the world''s lack of knowledge about God. Both passages emphasize that the world did not recognize Him, indicating a spiritual blindness to His presence and identity.', 'theme', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 10, 62, 3, 1, 1, 'the world knew him not', 'Connection of World and Knowledge', 'Both passages emphasize the world''s lack of recognition of divine presence. The phrase ''the world knew him not'' in John 1:10 parallels the idea that ''the world knoweth us not'' in 1 John 3:1, highlighting a shared theme of misunderstanding or ignorance towards God and His followers.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 10, 46, 1, 21, 21, 'the world knew him not', 'World''s Knowledge of God', 'This connection highlights the theme of the world''s failure to recognize God. Both passages emphasize that the world, despite being created by Him, does not know Him, illustrating a consistent biblical motif of divine revelation versus human ignorance.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 10, 46, 2, 8, 8, 'the world knew him not', 'World''s Ignorance of Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of the world''s failure to recognize Jesus. Both passages emphasize that the world and its leaders did not know Him, leading to significant consequences.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 10, 40, 11, 27, 27, 'the world knew him not', 'Knowledge of the Son', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of knowledge and recognition. John 1:10 states that ''the world knew him not,'' while Matthew 11:27 highlights that ''no man knoweth the Son, but the Father.'' This connection underscores the limited understanding of Jesus by the world.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 10, 44, 17, 24, 27, 'the world was made by him', 'Creation and Human Response', 'Both passages emphasize that God made the world and all things within it. They highlight the theme of humanity''s failure to recognize or seek God, as seen in the phrase ''the world knew him not'' and the call to ''seek the Lord.''', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 10, 58, 11, 3, 3, 'the world was made by him', 'Creation and Recognition of God', 'Both passages emphasize the act of creation by God, with John highlighting that ''the world was made by him'' and Hebrews stating that ''the worlds were framed by the word of God.'' This connection highlights the theme of God''s creative power and the world''s failure to recognize Him.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 11, 23, 53, 2, 3, 'his own received him not', 'Rejection of the Messiah', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of rejection. John 1:11 states that ''his own received him not,'' while Isaiah 53:3 describes him as ''despised and rejected of men.'' This connection highlights the consistent portrayal of the Messiah''s unrecognized and unvalued nature.', 'theme', 0.552, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 11, 42, 19, 14, 14, 'his own received him not', 'Rejection of Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of a leader by his own people. In John 1:11, ''his own received him not'' parallels the citizens in Luke 19:14 who declare, ''We will not have this man to reign over us.''', 'theme', 0.552, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 11, 43, 3, 32, 32, 'received him not', 'Rejection of Testimony Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of Jesus'' message. In John 1:11, his own people did not receive him, while in John 3:32, it states that no man receives his testimony.', 'theme', 0.46799999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 11, 44, 7, 51, 52, 'his own received him not', 'Rejection of the Just One', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of Jesus by his own people. John 1:11 states that ''his own received him not,'' while Acts 7:51-52 highlights the resistance to the Holy Ghost and the persecution of prophets, culminating in the betrayal of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 11, 42, 20, 13, 15, 'his own received him not', 'Rejection of the Beloved Son', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of the beloved son. In John 1:11, ''his own received him not,'' parallels the husbandmen''s decision to kill the son in Luke 20:14. This connection highlights the theme of rejection faced by the son.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 11, 40, 15, 24, 24, 'his own received him not', 'Rejection of Jesus by Israel', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' mission to Israel and their rejection of him. Both passages emphasize the idea that he came specifically to his own people, yet they did not receive him.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 11, 45, 15, 8, 8, 'his own received him not', 'Rejection and Ministry of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the contrast between Jesus'' rejection by his own and his role as a minister to the circumcision. Both passages emphasize the significance of Jesus'' mission to the Jewish people, despite their initial rejection.', 'theme', 0.363, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 12, 45, 8, 14, 14, 'sons of God', 'Sons of God Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of becoming ''sons of God.'' John 1:12 speaks of receiving Christ to gain this status, while Romans 8:14 highlights being led by the Spirit as a defining characteristic of being a son of God.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 12, 48, 3, 26, 26, 'sons of God', 'Children of God by Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of becoming ''children of God'' through faith in Christ. John 1:12 speaks of receiving Him to gain this status, while Galatians 3:26 affirms that faith in Christ Jesus makes one a child of God.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 12, 62, 3, 1, 1, 'sons of God', 'Connection of Sonship in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of becoming ''sons of God.'' John 1:12 speaks of the power given to believers to become sons, while 1 John 3:1 celebrates the love that allows believers to be called sons of God.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 12, 47, 6, 17, 18, 'sons of God', 'Sons of God Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of becoming sons of God through belief and separation from unclean things. The promise of being received as sons and daughters in 2 Corinthians echoes the empowerment given to believers in John.', 'theme', 0.8180000000000001, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 12, 48, 4, 6, 6, 'sons of God', 'Sons of God Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of becoming sons of God. John 1:12 speaks of receiving power to become sons, while Galatians 4:6 affirms that believers are indeed sons, highlighting their relationship with God.', 'theme', 0.776, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 12, 43, 3, 18, 18, 'believe on his name', 'Connection of Belief and Condemnation', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of belief in Jesus. John 1:12 highlights that those who receive Him gain the power to become sons of God, while John 3:18 states that belief is crucial to avoid condemnation.', 'theme', 0.713, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 12, 40, 10, 40, 40, 'received him', 'Connection of Reception and Belief', 'This connection highlights the theme of receiving. Both passages emphasize that receiving Jesus or his messengers is linked to becoming part of God''s family.', 'theme', 0.622, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 13, 62, 3, 9, 9, NULL, 'Connection of Being Born of God', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being ''born of God.'' The first passage indicates that this new birth is initiated by God, while the second passage describes the moral implications of being born of God, specifically regarding sin.', 'theme', 0.482, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 13, 59, 1, 18, 18, 'of God', 'Connection of Divine Birth', 'Both passages emphasize being ''born'' or ''begat'' by God, highlighting the divine origin of believers. They reflect the theme of spiritual rebirth through God''s will, not human effort.', 'theme', 0.475, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 13, 60, 1, 23, 23, 'born, not of blood', 'Connection of New Birth', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being ''born'' in a spiritual sense. John 1:13 highlights that this new birth is ''of God,'' while 1 Peter 1:23 contrasts ''corruptible seed'' with ''incorruptible'' by the word of God.', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 13, 43, 3, 5, 8, NULL, 'Connection of Spiritual Birth', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of being born of God and the Spirit. They highlight the distinction between physical birth and spiritual rebirth, underscoring that true life comes from divine origin.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 1, 13, 60, 1, 3, 3, NULL, 'New Birth and Divine Origin', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being ''born'' or ''begotten'' by God. John 1:13 highlights that this birth is not of human origin, while 1 Peter 1:3 speaks of being begotten again through God''s mercy. This connection highlights the divine initiative in the process of spiritual rebirth.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
