(43, 16, 2, 44, 26, 9, 11, 'put you out of the synagogues', 'Persecution of Believers', 'Both passages emphasize the persecution of believers, with John 16:2 predicting that those who kill Christians will believe they are serving God. Acts 26:9-11 illustrates this by detailing Paul''s actions against Christians, including imprisoning and punishing them in synagogues.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 2, 45, 10, 2, 3, 'whosoever killeth you will think', 'Zeal and Misguided Actions', 'This connection highlights the theme of misguided zeal in both passages. John 16:2 speaks of those who kill believers thinking they serve God, while Romans 10:2-3 addresses a zeal for God that lacks knowledge, leading to the establishment of their own righteousness.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 2, 40, 10, 28, 28, 'whosoever killeth you will think', 'Fear of Persecution and Death', 'This connection highlights the theme of persecution faced by believers, as both passages address the consequences of faith. John 16:2 mentions those who kill believers thinking they serve God, while Matthew 10:28 encourages not to fear those who can kill the body, emphasizing the greater concern for the soul.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 2, 44, 22, 3, 4, 'whosoever killeth you will think', 'Persecution of Believers', 'This connection highlights the theme of persecution faced by early Christians. Both passages emphasize the idea that those who persecute believers, like Paul in Acts, believe they are serving God, as noted in John.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 2, 43, 12, 42, 42, NULL, 'Fear of Exclusion from Synagogue', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of being put out of the synagogue. In John 16:2, the threat of expulsion is linked to persecution, while John 12:42 shows that this fear prevents belief in Jesus among the rulers.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 2, 66, 6, 9, 9, 'whosoever killeth you will think', 'Persecution for Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the suffering of believers due to their faith. John 16:2 speaks of being killed for service to God, while Revelation 6:9 describes those slain for their testimony of God''s word.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 3, 43, 15, 21, 21, NULL, 'Connection of Persecution for Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the reason for persecution faced by believers, which is linked to the lack of knowledge of God. The phrase ''know not'' in both verses highlights this common theme of ignorance regarding the Father and the one who sent Jesus.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 3, 43, 17, 25, 25, 'not known the Father', 'Knowledge of the Father', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of knowing the Father. In John 16:3, the lack of knowledge about the Father leads to persecution, while John 17:25 highlights that the world has not known Him, contrasting with Jesus and His followers who do know Him.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 3, 53, 1, 8, 8, NULL, 'Connection of Knowledge and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of not knowing God. John 16:3 refers to those who do not know the Father or Jesus, while 2 Thessalonians 1:8 speaks of vengeance on those who know not God. This connection highlights the theme of divine judgment linked to a lack of knowledge.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 3, 53, 2, 10, 12, 'have not known the Father, nor me', 'Connection of Knowledge and Truth', 'This connection highlights the theme of knowing God and the truth. Both passages emphasize the consequences of not knowing the Father and rejecting the truth, leading to spiritual deception and judgment.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 3, 62, 3, 1, 1, 'because they have not known the Father', 'Connection of Knowledge and Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of knowledge and identity in relation to God. John 16:3 states that the world does not know the Father or Jesus, while 1 John 3:1 explains that the world does not know believers because it did not know Him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 3, 42, 10, 22, 22, 'not known the Father, nor me', 'Knowledge of the Father and Son', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of knowing the Father and the Son. John 16:3 highlights the lack of knowledge about the Father and the Son, while Luke 10:22 states that only the Father knows the Son, and vice versa, underscoring the exclusivity of this knowledge.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 3, 46, 2, 8, 8, 'not known the Father, nor me', 'Ignorance of the Divine', 'This connection highlights the theme of ignorance regarding God and Jesus. Both passages emphasize that a lack of knowledge about the Father and the Son leads to significant actions, such as persecution and crucifixion.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 4, 43, 14, 29, 29, 'that when the time shall come', 'Connection of Forewarning and Belief', 'Both passages emphasize the act of foretelling events to strengthen belief. The phrase ''I have told you before it come to pass'' in John 14:29 parallels the idea of remembering warnings in John 16:4.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 4, 41, 13, 23, 23, NULL, 'Foretelling and Remembrance', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of foretelling events. John 16:4 speaks of remembering what was foretold, while Mark 13:23 asserts that all things have been foretold.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 4, 43, 13, 19, 19, NULL, 'Foretelling and Belief Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of foretelling events to strengthen belief. John 16:4 speaks of remembering prior warnings, while John 13:19 focuses on believing when prophecies come to pass.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 4, 40, 9, 15, 15, NULL, 'Connection of Mourning and Absence', 'This connection highlights the theme of mourning in relation to the absence of Jesus. In John 16:4, Jesus prepares his followers for a time when he will no longer be with them, paralleling Matthew 9:15, which speaks of the mourning that will occur when the bridegroom is taken away.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 4, 40, 24, 25, 25, NULL, 'Forewarning of Future Events', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of prior warnings given by Jesus. John 16:4 states that Jesus told them things in advance, while Matthew 24:25 reiterates that he has informed them beforehand.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 4, 23, 41, 22, 23, 'that when the time shall come', 'Connection of Foretelling Events', 'This connection highlights the theme of foretelling future events. Both passages emphasize the importance of remembering prior warnings and understanding what is to come.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 4, 41, 2, 19, 19, 'I told you of them', 'Presence of the Bridegroom', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of Jesus'' presence. In John 16:4, Jesus indicates that his teachings will be remembered when he is no longer with them, while Mark 2:19 highlights that fasting is not appropriate while the bridegroom is present.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 5, 43, 13, 36, 36, 'Whither goest thou?', 'Connection of Jesus'' Departure', 'Both passages emphasize the question of Jesus'' departure. In John 16:5, Jesus notes that none of his disciples ask where he is going, while in John 13:36, Peter directly asks, ''Whither goest thou?''', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 5, 43, 7, 33, 33, NULL, 'Departure to the Father', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' impending departure to the one who sent him. This connection highlights the continuity of Jesus'' mission and the acknowledgment of his return to the Father.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 5, 49, 4, 7, 11, 'Whither goest thou?', 'Ascension and Gifts Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of Christ''s ascension and the subsequent giving of gifts to believers. In John 16:5, Jesus speaks of going to the one who sent him, while Ephesians 4:7-11 describes how, after his ascension, he gives gifts to men.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 5, 58, 1, 3, 3, 'I go my way to him that sent me', 'Departure and Divine Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' departure to the Father, as mentioned in John 16:5, and his subsequent exaltation at the right hand of God in Hebrews 1:3. Both passages emphasize the significance of Jesus'' movement from earth to a position of divine authority.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 5, 58, 12, 2, 2, 'Whither goest thou?', 'Connection of Departure and Ascension', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' departure to the Father in John 16:5 and his exaltation at the right hand of God in Hebrews 12:2. Both passages emphasize the significance of Jesus'' journey and ultimate purpose.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 6, 43, 14, 1, 1, 'sorrow hath filled your heart', 'Connection of Troubled Hearts', 'Both passages emphasize the state of the heart in times of distress. John 16:6 mentions sorrow filling the heart, while John 14:1 encourages not to let the heart be troubled.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 6, 42, 24, 17, 17, 'sorrow hath filled your heart', 'Connection of Sorrow and Sadness', 'Both passages emphasize the emotional state of sorrow and sadness experienced by the disciples. In John, their hearts are filled with sorrow, while in Luke, they are described as sad during their conversation.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 6, 43, 16, 20, 22, 'sorrow hath filled your heart', 'Connection of Sorrow and Joy', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of sorrow transforming into joy. In John 16:6, the disciples'' sorrow is acknowledged, while John 16:20-22 assures them that their sorrow will eventually lead to joy, akin to a woman''s childbirth experience.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 6, 43, 20, 11, 15, 'sorrow hath filled your heart', 'Connection of Sorrow and Weeping', 'This connection highlights the theme of sorrow present in both passages. In John 16:6, Jesus acknowledges the sorrow in the hearts of His disciples, while in John 20:11-15, Mary expresses her sorrow through weeping at the tomb.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 6, 42, 22, 45, 45, 'sorrow hath filled your heart', 'Sorrow in Disciples'' Hearts', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of sorrow affecting the disciples. In John, their hearts are filled with sorrow, while in Luke, they are found sleeping due to sorrow.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 6, 43, 14, 27, 28, 'sorrow hath filled your heart', 'Connection of Sorrow and Peace', 'This connection highlights the transition from sorrow to peace. In John 16:6, the disciples'' hearts are filled with sorrow, while John 14:27-28 offers them peace and encouragement not to be troubled.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 7, 43, 14, 26, 26, 'the Comforter', 'Connection of the Comforter', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Comforter, identified as the Holy Ghost, in teaching and reminding the disciples. John 16:7 indicates the necessity of Jesus'' departure for the Comforter to come, while John 14:26 describes the Comforter''s function in their lives.', 'theme', 0.573, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 7, 43, 14, 16, 17, 'the Comforter will not come unto you', 'Connection of the Comforter', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Comforter, highlighting the necessity of Jesus'' departure for the Spirit''s arrival. John 16:7 states that the Comforter will come if Jesus departs, while John 14:16-17 introduces the Comforter as the Spirit of truth that will dwell with believers.', 'theme', 0.46799999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 7, 44, 2, 33, 33, 'the Comforter will not come unto you', 'Connection of the Holy Spirit', 'This connection highlights the promise of the Comforter in John 16:7 and the fulfillment of that promise in Acts 2:33. Both passages emphasize the sending of the Holy Spirit as a significant event in the early church.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 7, 42, 24, 49, 49, 'the Comforter will not come unto you', 'Connection of the Comforter and Power', 'Both passages emphasize the sending of divine assistance. John speaks of the Comforter coming after Jesus departs, while Luke mentions the promise of power from on high, indicating a connection between the two events.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 7, 44, 1, 4, 5, 'the Comforter will not come unto you', 'Promise of the Holy Spirit', 'This connection highlights the promise of the Comforter in John 16:7 and the subsequent baptism with the Holy Ghost in Acts 1:4-5. Both passages emphasize the importance of waiting for the Holy Spirit''s arrival after Jesus'' departure.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
