(43, 16, 7, 49, 4, 8, 13, 'if I go not away, the Comforter will not come', 'Connection of Ascension and Gifts', 'This connection highlights the significance of Jesus'' ascension in both passages. John 16:7 emphasizes the necessity of Jesus departing for the Comforter to come, while Ephesians 4:8-13 describes the gifts given to the church following His ascension.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 8, 44, 2, 37, 37, 'reprove the world of sin', 'Conviction of Sin and Response', 'This connection highlights the theme of conviction in both passages. John 16:8 speaks of the Holy Spirit reproving the world of sin, while Acts 2:37 shows the people''s hearts being pricked, prompting their inquiry about what to do.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 8, 65, 1, 15, 15, 'of judgment', 'Judgment and Conviction Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of judgment and the conviction of ungodly behavior. John 16:8 speaks of reproving the world of sin and judgment, while Jude 1:15 focuses on executing judgment and convincing the ungodly of their deeds.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 8, 38, 12, 10, 10, 'reprove the world of sin', 'Connection of Sin and Mourning', 'This connection highlights the themes of sin and mourning in both passages. John 16:8 speaks of reproving the world of sin, while Zechariah 12:10 describes mourning for the one who was pierced, indicating a recognition of sin and its consequences.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 8, 43, 8, 9, 9, 'reprove the world of sin', 'Conviction of Sin and Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of conviction present in both passages. In John 16:8, the Holy Spirit reproves the world of sin, while in John 8:9, those present are convicted by their own conscience, leading to judgment.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 8, 44, 16, 29, 30, 'reprove the world of sin', 'Conviction and Salvation', 'This connection highlights the theme of conviction of sin leading to a response for salvation. In John 16:8, the Holy Spirit reproves the world of sin, while in Acts 16:30, the jailer, recognizing his need for salvation, asks what he must do.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 8, 46, 14, 24, 24, 'he will reprove the world of sin', 'Conviction and Judgment in Context', 'This connection highlights the theme of conviction and judgment present in both passages. John 16:8 speaks of reproving the world of sin and judgment, while 1 Corinthians 14:24 discusses how an unbeliever is judged by the prophetic words of believers.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 8, 43, 8, 46, 46, 'of sin', 'Connection of Conviction and Sin', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of sin and the act of convincing or reproving regarding it. John 16:8 speaks of reproving the world of sin, while John 8:46 questions who can convincingly accuse him of sin.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 9, 43, 15, 22, 25, 'Of sin, because they believe not on me;', 'Connection of Sin and Unbelief', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of sin in relation to belief in Jesus. John 16:9 highlights sin due to unbelief, while John 15:22-25 discusses the accountability of those who reject Him after His revelation. This connection underscores the seriousness of rejecting Christ.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 9, 43, 8, 23, 24, 'because they believe not on me', 'Connection of Belief and Sin', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of belief in Jesus for salvation. John 16:9 states that sin is linked to unbelief, while John 8:24 warns that dying in sins is a consequence of not believing that Jesus is the Messiah.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 9, 41, 16, 16, 16, 'believe not on me', 'Connection of Belief and Salvation', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of belief in relation to salvation. John 16:9 highlights sin as a result of unbelief, while Mark 16:16 states that those who do not believe will be condemned.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 9, 58, 3, 12, 12, 'believe not on me', 'Connection of Unbelief and Sin', 'This connection highlights the theme of unbelief as a root of sin. Both passages emphasize the danger of departing from faith in God, linking unbelief directly to sinfulness.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 9, 44, 2, 22, 38, 'Of sin, because they believe not on me;', 'Connection of Sin and Belief', 'This connection highlights the theme of sin linked to disbelief in Jesus. In John 16:9, sin is defined as not believing in Him, while Acts 2:38 calls for repentance and belief in Jesus for the remission of sins.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 9, 44, 3, 14, 19, 'Of sin, because they believe not on me;', 'Connection of Sin and Repentance', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of sin resulting from unbelief and the call to repentance. John 16:9 highlights sin due to disbelief in Jesus, while Acts 3:19 urges repentance for the denial of Christ, linking the two concepts.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 9, 58, 10, 28, 29, 'Of sin, because they believe not on me;', 'Connection of Sin and Rejection', 'Both passages emphasize the seriousness of rejecting God. John 16:9 highlights sin as unbelief in Christ, while Hebrews 10:28-29 warns of severe punishment for those who disregard the Son of God. This connection highlights the gravity of unbelief and its consequences.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 10, 47, 5, 21, 21, 'righteousness', 'Righteousness and Sin Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of righteousness. John 16:10 mentions righteousness in relation to Jesus'' departure, while 2 Corinthians 5:21 speaks of being made the righteousness of God through Christ, who took on sin for humanity.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
