(43, 16, 10, 46, 1, 30, 30, 'of righteousness', 'Connection of Righteousness in Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of righteousness in both passages. John 16:10 refers to righteousness linked to Jesus'' departure, while 1 Corinthians 1:30 identifies Christ as our righteousness.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 10, 50, 3, 7, 9, 'righteousness, because I go to my Father', 'Righteousness and Loss for Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of righteousness in both passages. John 16:10 mentions righteousness in relation to Jesus'' departure, while Philippians 3:9 contrasts personal righteousness with the righteousness through faith in Christ.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 11, 43, 12, 31, 31, 'the prince of this world is judged', 'Judgment and the Prince', 'Both passages emphasize the judgment of the world and the prince of this world. John 16:11 states that the prince is judged, while John 12:31 declares that he will be cast out, highlighting a direct connection in their themes of judgment.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 11, 62, 3, 8, 8, 'the prince of this world is judged', 'Judgment and the Devil''s Works', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment against the devil. Both passages emphasize the defeat of the devil''s influence, with John 16:11 stating that ''the prince of this world is judged'' and 1 John 3:8 mentioning the purpose of the Son of God to ''destroy the works of the devil.''', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 11, 43, 14, 30, 30, 'prince of this world', 'Judgment of the Prince', 'Both passages emphasize the ''prince of this world'' and his judgment. John 16:11 states that this prince is judged, while John 14:30 indicates his coming and lack of claim over Jesus.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 11, 51, 2, 15, 15, 'prince of this world is judged', 'Judgment of the Prince', 'This connection highlights the judgment of the ''prince of this world'' in John 16:11 and the triumph over ''principalities and powers'' in Colossians 2:15. Both passages emphasize the defeat of spiritual authorities, indicating a shared theme of victory over evil.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 11, 58, 2, 14, 14, 'the prince of this world is judged', 'Judgment and Power of Death', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment against evil. Both passages emphasize the defeat of the devil and the judgment of the prince of this world.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 11, 47, 4, 4, 4, 'prince of this world is judged', 'Judgment and the God of This World', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment against the ''prince of this world'' and the ''god of this world,'' both indicating a spiritual authority that opposes God. The judgment mentioned in John 16:11 relates to the blinding influence described in 2 Corinthians 4:4, suggesting a shared focus on spiritual deception and authority.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 11, 23, 49, 24, 26, 'the prince of this world is judged', 'Judgment and Deliverance Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment against oppressive forces. Both passages emphasize the deliverance of captives and the judgment of the powerful, as seen in ''the prince of this world is judged'' and the promise of deliverance from ''the mighty.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 12, 41, 4, 33, 33, 'cannot bear them now', 'Understanding Spiritual Capacity', 'Both passages emphasize the limitation of understanding among the listeners. John 16:12 indicates that the disciples cannot bear more teachings, while Mark 4:33 notes that Jesus spoke in parables as the audience was able to hear them.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 12, 43, 15, 15, 15, NULL, 'Understanding Revelation and Friendship', 'This connection highlights the transition from servitude to friendship, emphasizing the knowledge shared by Jesus. In John 16:12, Jesus indicates there are more teachings to come, while in John 15:15, He states that He has made known all things from the Father, suggesting a deepening relationship and understanding.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 12, 46, 3, 1, 2, 'cannot bear them now', 'Spiritual Maturity and Understanding', 'Both passages emphasize the inability to bear deeper truths. John notes that the disciples cannot handle more, while Paul indicates the Corinthians are still not ready for solid food.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 12, 44, 1, 3, 3, 'many things to say unto you', 'Unrevealed Teachings and Kingdom Insights', 'This connection highlights the transition from Jesus'' unspoken teachings in John to the revelations about the kingdom of God in Acts. Both passages emphasize the importance of understanding deeper truths over time.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 12, 58, 5, 11, 14, 'many things to say', 'Spiritual Maturity and Understanding', 'Both passages emphasize the challenges of spiritual growth and understanding. John 16:12 speaks of uncommunicated truths due to the disciples'' inability to bear them, while Hebrews 5:11-14 addresses the need for deeper teachings that the audience cannot yet grasp, highlighting their spiritual immaturity.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 12, 43, 14, 30, 30, 'I have yet many things to say', 'Communication Limitations in Discourse', 'Both passages emphasize the limitations of communication. In John 16:12, Jesus acknowledges that there are many things to say, but the disciples cannot bear them now, while in John 14:30, He indicates a reduction in conversation due to the impending presence of the prince of this world.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
